        <div class="col">
          <div class="card mt-2 m-lg-2">
            <div class="bg-image" style="background-image: url('https://i.pinimg.com/736x/73/c1/f6/73c1f6aa0d92b9d374edac5f4ac5dae6.jpg');">
            <img src="Butter-Chicken.jpg" class="card-img-top mx-auto d-block mt-2" alt="...">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h3 class="card-title text-center"><b>Butter Chicken</b></h3>
              <div class="card-body overflow-auto " style="max-height: 200px;">
                <p class="text-light">Ingredients:</p><li class="text-light">boneless chicken pieces</li><li class="text-light">2 tablespoons butter</li><li class="text-light">2 tablespoons butter</li><li class="text-light">1 onion, finely chopped</li>
                    <li class="text-light">tomatoes, pureed</li> <li class="text-light">1/2 cup heavy cream</li><li class="text-light">1/2 cup plain yogurt</li>
                    <li class="text-light">2 cloves garlic, minced</li><li class="text-light">1-inch piece of ginger, minced</li><li class="text-light">1 tablespoon garam masala</li>
                    <li class="text-light">1 teaspoon cumin</li><li class="text-light">1 teaspoon paprika</li><li class="text-light">1 teaspoon chili powder</li> 
                    <li class="text-light">Salt and pepper to taste</li><li class="text-light">Fresh cilantro for garnish</li>
                    <p class="text-light"><br>Instructions:</p>
                    <li class="text-light">Marinate the chicken pieces with yogurt, garlic, ginger, half of the garam masala, cumin, paprika, and chili powder. Let it sit for at least 30 minutes.</li>
                    <li class="text-light">In a large skillet, melt the butter over medium heat. Add the chopped onions and sauté until they become translucent.</li>
                    <li class="text-light">Add the marinated chicken and cook until it's no longer pink.</li>
                    <li class="text-light">Pour in the tomato puree and the remaining garam masala. Simmer for a few minutes.</li>
                    <li class="text-light">Stir in the heavy cream and season with salt and pepper. Simmer for another 10 minutes until the sauce thickens.</li>
                    <li class="text-light">Garnish with fresh cilantro and serve hot with rice or naan.</li>
            </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col">
          <div class="card mt-2">
            <div class="bg-image" style="background-image: url('https://i.pinimg.com/736x/73/c1/f6/73c1f6aa0d92b9d374edac5f4ac5dae6.jpg');">
            <img src="gulab-jamun-12.jpg" class="card-img-top mx-auto d-block mt-2" alt="...">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h3 class="card-title text-center"><b>Gulab Jamun</b></h3>
              <div class="card-body overflow-auto " style="max-height: 200px;">
                <p class="text-light">Ingredients:</p><p class="text-light">For Gulab Jamun Balls:</p><li class="text-light">1 cup of milk powder</li><li class="text-light">1/4 cup of all-purpose flour</li><li class="text-light">1/4 teaspoon of baking soda</li><li class="text-light">2 tablespoons of ghee (clarified butter)</li><li class="text-light">A little milk (about 1/4 cup) to knead the dough</li>
                <li class="text-light">Oil or ghee for deep frying</li><p class="text-light"><br>For the Sugar Syrup:</p><li class="text-light">1 cup of sugar</li><li class="text-light">1 cup of water</li><li class="text-light">A few saffron strands (optional)</li><li class="text-light">A pinch of cardamom powder</li><p class="text-light">Instructions:</p>
                <li class="text-light">In a mixing bowl, combine the milk powder, all-purpose flour, and baking soda. Mix them together.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Add ghee to the dry ingredients and rub the mixture between your palms to incorporate the ghee evenly.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Gradually add a little milk at a time and knead the mixture into a smooth, soft, and pliable dough. Be careful not to make it too sticky or too dry.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Divide the dough into small, equal-sized portions and roll them into smooth balls. Make sure there are no cracks on the surface of the balls.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Heat oil or ghee in a deep pan over medium-low heat. The oil should be medium hot, not too hot, to avoid burning the Gulab Jamun.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Carefully slide the prepared Gulab Jamun balls into the hot oil one by one. Fry them on low to medium heat until they turn golden brown. Ensure the heat isn't too high, as you want the insides to get cooked and the outside to be evenly browned.</li>  
                <li class="text-light">While the Gulab Jamun is frying, prepare the sugar syrup. In a separate pan, combine sugar and water. Bring it to a boil, then simmer for a few minutes until it slightly thickens. You can add saffron strands and cardamom powder for flavor.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Once the Gulab Jamun balls are golden brown, remove them from the oil and immediately place them into the warm sugar syrup. Allow them to soak in the syrup for at least 1-2 hours.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Serve Gulab Jamun warm or at room temperature, garnished with chopped nuts if desired.</li>              
            </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col">
          <div class="card mt-2">
            <div class="bg-image" style="background-image: url('https://i.pinimg.com/736x/73/c1/f6/73c1f6aa0d92b9d374edac5f4ac5dae6.jpg');">
            <img src="biriyani.jpg" class="card-img-top mx-auto d-block mt-2" alt="...">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h3 class="card-title text-center"><b>Biriyani</b></h3>
              <div class="card-body overflow-auto " style="max-height: 200px;">
                <p class="text-light">Ingredients:</p><li class="text-light">2 cups of basmati rice</li><li class="text-light">500g of chicken, lamb, or vegetables</li><li class="text-light">2 onions, thinly sliced</li><li class="text-light">2 tomatoes, chopped</li><li class="text-light">1/4 cup of plain yogurt</li><li class="text-light">2 tablespoons of biryani masala</li><li class="text-light">1 tablespoon of ginger-garlic paste</li><li class="text-light">2-3 green chilies, slit</li><li class="text-light">A handful of fresh mint and cilantro leaves</li><li class="text-light">4 cups of water</li><li class="text-light">2 tablespoons of ghee (clarified butter) or oil</li><li class="text-light">Salt to taste</li><p class="text-light"><br>For Layering:</p>
                <li class="text-light">Saffron strands soaked in warm milk (for color)</li><li class="text-light">Ghee for drizzling</li><li class="text-light">Fried onions for garnish</li><p class="text-light"><br>Instructions:</p>
                <li class="text-light">Wash the rice thoroughly and soak it in water for about 30 minutes. Drain and set aside.</li>
                <li class="text-light">In a large pot or pressure cooker, heat ghee or oil. Add sliced onions and cook until they turn golden brown. Remove half of the fried onions for garnishing.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Add ginger-garlic paste, green chilies, and chopped tomatoes to the pot. Sauté until the tomatoes become soft and the oil starts to separate.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Add the biryani masala and cook for a couple of minutes.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Stir in the meat or vegetables and cook for a few minutes, allowing them to brown slightly.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Add yogurt, mint leaves, cilantro leaves, and salt. Cook for another few minutes until the meat or vegetables are well coated with the mixture.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Add the soaked and drained rice to the pot. Mix gently to combine the rice with the meat and spices.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Add water and bring the mixture to a boil. Once it starts boiling, reduce the heat to low, cover the pot, and let it simmer until the rice is cooked and the water is absorbed. If you're using a pressure cooker, do not place the weight, and allow it to cook on low heat for about 15-20 minutes.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Once the rice is cooked, drizzle saffron milk and ghee over the top. Cover the pot with a tight-fitting lid and let it sit on very low heat for another 10-15 minutes. This allows the flavors to meld together.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Garnish with the reserved fried onions.</li>
            </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col">
          <div class="card m-lg-2">
            <div class="bg-image" style="background-image: url('https://i.pinimg.com/736x/73/c1/f6/73c1f6aa0d92b9d374edac5f4ac5dae6.jpg');">
            <img src="samosa.webp" class="card-img-top mx-auto d-block mt-2" alt="...">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h3 class="card-title text-center"><b>Samosa</b></h3>
              <div class="card-body overflow-auto " style="max-height: 200px;">
                <p class="text-light">Ingredients:</p><p class="text-light">For the Samosa Dough:</p><li class="text-light">2 cups of all-purpose flour</li><li class="text-light">1/4 cup of vegetable oil</li><li class="text-light">A pinch of salt</li><li class="text-light">Water for kneading</li><p class="text-light"><br>For the Samosa Filling:</p>
                <li class="text-light">2 cups of boiled and mashed potatoes</li><li class="text-light">1/2 cup of boiled peas</li><li class="text-light">1 tablespoon of oil</li><li class="text-light">1 teaspoon of cumin seeds</li><li class="text-light">1 teaspoon of ginger-garlic paste</li><li class="text-light">1/2 teaspoon of turmeric</li><li class="text-light">1 teaspoon of ground coriander</li><li class="text-light">1 teaspoon of garam masala</li><li class="text-light">1/2 teaspoon of red chili powder (adjust to taste)</li><li class="text-light">Salt to taste</li><li class="text-light">Chopped cilantro for garnish</li><p class="text-light"><br>Instructions:</p>
                <li class="text-light">Prepare the dough by mixing flour, a pinch of salt, and oil. Gradually add water and knead until you have a smooth, firm dough. Cover it with a damp cloth and let it rest for 30 minutes.</li>
                <li class="text-light">In a pan, heat oil and add cumin seeds. Sauté until they crackle.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Add ginger-garlic paste and sauté for a minute until the raw smell disappears.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Add turmeric, ground coriander, garam masala, red chili powder, and salt. Cook for a few minutes until the spices are well combined.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Add boiled and mashed potatoes and boiled peas. Mix everything together and cook for a few more minutes. Remove from heat and let the filling cool.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Preheat oil for deep frying in a pan.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Divide the dough into small balls and roll each ball into a thin oval or round shape.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Cut the rolled dough in half to form two semi-circles. Take one semi-circle, fold it in half to form a cone, and seal the edges with a little water to make a triangular pocket.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Fill the pocket with the prepared potato and pea mixture and seal the top by folding the edge over.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Deep fry the samosas in hot oil until they are golden brown and crispy. Drain excess oil on paper towels.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Serve the samosas hot with chutney or tamarind sauce.</li>
            </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="col">
        <div class="card">
          <div class="bg-image" style="background-image: url('https://i.pinimg.com/736x/73/c1/f6/73c1f6aa0d92b9d374edac5f4ac5dae6.jpg');">
          <img src="aloo paratha.jpg" class="card-img-top mx-auto d-block mt-2" alt="...">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h3 class="card-title text-center"><b>Aloo Paratha</b></h3>
            <div class="card-body overflow-auto " style="max-height: 200px;">
                <p class="text-light">Ingredients:</p><p class="text-light">For the Paratha Dough:</p><li class="text-light">2 cups whole wheat flour</li><li class="text-light">Water for kneading</li><li class="text-light">A pinch of salt</li><p class="text-light"><br>For the Aloo Paratha Filling:</p>
                <li class="text-light">2-3 medium-sized boiled and mashed potatoes</li><li class="text-light">1 small onion, finely chopped (optional)</li><li class="text-light">1-2 green chilies, finely chopped (adjust to taste)</li><li class="text-light">1/2 teaspoon cumin seeds</li><li class="text-light">1/2 teaspoon red chili powder (adjust to taste)</li><li class="text-light">1/2 teaspoon garam masala</li><li class="text-light">Salt to taste</li><li class="text-light">Chopped fresh cilantro (coriander leaves)</li><p class="text-light"><br>Instructions:</p>
                <li class="text-light">In a mixing bowl, combine the whole wheat flour, a pinch of salt, and enough water to knead into a smooth and soft dough. Cover and let it rest for about 15-20 minutes.</li>
                <li class="text-light">In another bowl, mix the mashed potatoes with finely chopped onions (if using), green chilies, cumin seeds, red chili powder, garam masala, salt, and chopped fresh cilantro. This forms the stuffing for your parathas.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Divide the dough into equal-sized portions and roll each portion into a ball.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Roll out one dough ball into a small circle, place a portion of the potato filling in the center, and enclose the filling by bringing the edges of the dough together.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Roll it back into a circle gently. Ensure that the filling is evenly distributed inside.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Heat a griddle or a flat pan on medium-high heat.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Place a stuffed paratha on the hot griddle and cook until small bubbles form on the surface.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Flip it over and apply a little oil or ghee on this side. Cook until both sides are golden brown and crispy.</li>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col">
        <div class="card">
          <div class="bg-image" style="background-image: url('https://i.pinimg.com/736x/73/c1/f6/73c1f6aa0d92b9d374edac5f4ac5dae6.jpg');">
          <img src="Masala-Dosa.jpg" class="card-img-top mx-auto d-block mt-2" alt="...">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h3 class="card-title text-center"><b>Masala Dosa</b></h3>
            <div class="card-body overflow-auto " style="max-height: 200px;">
                <p class="text-light">Ingredients:</p><p class="text-light">For Dosa Batter:</p><li class="text-light">1 cup rice</li><li class="text-light">1/4 cup urad dal (black gram lentils)</li><li class="text-light">A pinch of fenugreek seeds</li><li class="text-light">Water for soaking</li><li class="text-light">Salt to taste</li><p class="text-light"><br>For Masala (Potato Filling):</p>
                <li class="text-light">2-3 large potatoes, boiled and mashed</li><li class="text-light">1 onion, finely chopped</li><li class="text-light">1-2 green chilies, chopped (adjust to taste)</li><li class="text-light">1/2 teaspoon mustard seeds</li><li class="text-light">1/2 teaspoon cumin seeds</li><li class="text-light">A pinch of asafoetida (hing)</li><li class="text-light">Curry leaves</li><li class="text-light">Turmeric powder</li><li class="text-light">Oil for cooking</li><li class="text-light">Salt to taste</li><p class="text-light"><br>Instructions:</p>
                <li class="text-light">Wash the rice and urad dal separately and soak them in water along with fenugreek seeds for about 4-6 hours.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Grind the soaked rice and urad dal to make a smooth batter. Add salt and mix well. Let the batter ferment for 8-12 hours or overnight.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Heat oil in a pan and add mustard seeds. Let them splutter.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Add cumin seeds, asafoetida, and curry leaves. Sauté for a minute.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Add chopped onions and green chilies. Cook until the onions turn translucent.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Add turmeric powder and mashed potatoes. Mix well and cook for a few minutes.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Season with salt and set the potato filling aside.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Heat a flat non-stick griddle or a dosa pan.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Pour a ladleful of dosa batter onto the griddle and spread it in a circular motion to make a thin dosa.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Drizzle a little oil around the edges and on the dosa.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Cook until the dosa turns golden brown and crispy.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Place a portion of the potato filling in the center of the dosa.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Fold the dosa in half to cover the filling.</li>
                <li class="text-light">Serve hot with coconut chutney or sambar.</li>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    </div>

